     But if they are more than say 50 light years away, we would not know they were there. If they detected Marconi's first broadcast and replied to it, we would not have received their message.<br>
     More tellingly, if the laws of physics do not allow &quot;faster than light&quot; travel, you, as an alien head of a NASA type organisation, would not finance any probe, let alone a &quot;manned&quot; mission that would not be heard of for at least a hundred years - beyond your lifetime and beyond your next budgetary review...You get the drift? Presumably the laws of economics are the same everywhere, like those of physics? <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries>Unexplained Mysteries</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesufos>UFOs, Aliens & Abductions</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font> <IMG SRC="http://service.bfast.com/bfast/serve?bfmid=31103363&siteid=36236524&bfpage=qb3" BORDER="0" WIDTH="1" HEIGHT="1" NOSAVE >
